Certainly! Below is an example of a simple web app structured as a single HTML file with embedded CSS and JavaScript. You can copy this code into your own `.html` file to use it.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Simple Web App</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        h1 {
            color: #333;
        }
        #inputArea {
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        input[type="text"] {
            padding: 10px;
            width: 300px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            background-color: #5cb85c;
            color: white;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #4cae4c;
        }
        #output {
            margin-top: 20px;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            background-color: #fff;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h1>Simple Input Output App</h1>
    <div id="inputArea">
        <input type="text" id="userInput" placeholder="Type something...">
        <button onclick="processInput()">Submit</button>
    </div>
    <div id="output"></div>

    <script>
        function processInput() {
            const userInput = document.getElementById("userInput").value;
            const outputDiv = document.getElementById("output");
            if (userInput.trim() === "") {
                outputDiv.innerHTML = "<p style='color: red;'>Please enter something!</p>";
            } else {
                outputDiv.innerHTML = `<p>You entered: <strong>${userInput}</strong></p>`;
            }

            // Clear the input field after processing
            document.getElementById("userInput").value = '';
        }
    </script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions to Use:
1. Copy the code above.
2. Open a text editor (like Notepad or Visual Studio Code).
3. Paste the copied code into the editor.
4. Save the file with a `.html` extension, for example, `webapp.html`.
5. Open the saved file in a web browser to see and interact with the simple web app. 

This web app allows users to input text, submit it, and then displays what they entered. It also checks for empty input and gives feedback.
